ple together, Sarah J. King examines the community as a contested place, simultaneously Mi’kmaw and Canadian. Drawing on philosophy and indigenous, environmental, and religious studies, Fishing in Contested Waters demonstrates the deep roots of contemporary conflicts over rights, sovereignty, conservation, and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCulture conflictzNew BrunswickzBurnt Church. 0aLobster industryxSocial aspectszNew BrunswickzBurnt Church. 0aMicmac IndiansxFishingzNew BrunswickzBurnt Church. 0aMicmac IndianszNew BrunswickxClaims. 0aMicmac IndianszNew BrunswickxGovernment relations. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268993040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442689930423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442689930/original  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK